    <statement><p>Add or subtract the rational expressions to a single rational expression and then simplify. If applicable, state the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{3r}{r+3}+\frac{r}{r-3}-4} =}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-\frac{6\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{3r}{r+3}+\frac{r}{r-3}-4} 
      \amp = {\frac{3r}{r+3}} \cdot \frac{(r-3)}{(r-3)} + {\frac{r}{r-3}} \cdot \frac{(r+3)}{(r+3)} - \frac{4}{1} \cdot \frac{(r+3)(r-3)}{(r+3)(r-3)} \\
      \amp = \frac{3r(r-3)}{(r+3)(r-3)}  + \frac{r(r+3)}{(r+3)(r-3)} - \frac{4(r+3)(r-3)}{(r+3)(r-3)} \\
      \amp =  \frac{3r(r-3)+r(r+3)-4(r+3)(r-3)}{(r+3)(r-3)} \\
      \amp =  \frac{3r^{2}-9r+r^{2}+3r-4(r^{2}-9)}{(r+3)(r-3)} \\
      \amp =  \frac{3r^{2}-9r+r^{2}+3r-4r^{2}+36}{(r+3)(r-3)} \\
      \amp = {\frac{-6r+36}{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Notice that <m>{-\frac{6\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)}</m> is also correct. We should actually factor whenever possible, in case we can reduce the rational expression.</p>
</solution>
